%N A246638 Sequence a(n) = 2 + 3*A001519(n+1) appearing in a certain four circle touching problem together with A246639.
%C A246638 This sequence is motivated by Kival Ngaokrajang's touching circle problem considered in A092387 and A115032.
%C A246638 a(n), together with b(n) = A246639(n) appears as the curvature c(n) =  a(n) + (4*b(n)/5)*phi (phi = (1+sqrt(5))/2, golden section) of the circle which touches i) a circle of radius 5/4 (in some length units) divided by a chord of length 2 into two unequal parts, and ii) the two touching circles in the smaller part which have curvatures A092387(n) and  A092387(n+1), both also touching the circle with radius 5/4. See the illustration of Kival Ngaokrajang's link given in A092387, where the first circles in the smaller (upper) part are shown. The present circles will lie in the region between the large circle and two of these circles in the upper part.
%C A246638 Descartes' theorem on touching circles (see the links) is applied here as  c(n) = -4/5 + A(n) + A(n+1) + 2*sqrt((-4/5 )*(A(n) + A(n+1)) + A(n)*A(n+1)), with A(n) = A092387(n), n >= 0.
%C A246638 For the proof for the first formula for a(n) given below use the formula for the curvature A092387(n) = 2 + 2*S(n, 3) - 3* S(n-1, 3) (see the W. Lang link in A092387, part II) in c(n) and compare with a(n) from c(n) =  a(n) + (4*b(n)/5)*phi. This is done by using standard S-polynomial identities like the three term recurrence and the Cassini-Simson type identity
%C A246638   S(n, x)*S(n-2, x) = -1 + S(n-1, x)^2 (here for x=3). This implies S(n, 3)*S(n-1, 3) = (-1 + S(n, 3)^2 + S(n-1, 3)^2)/3. See also the mentioned link, part III a).
%C A246638 a(n) appears also in the curvature for the touching circles and chord problem in the smaller part of a circle with radius 5/4 dissected by a chord of length 2, together with A246640, where details are given.
